Stack implementation.

A stack does not need a special data structure — it is just an array or list with restricted access. In Python, a plain list makes a perfectly good stack. The append method pushes to the end — the logical top — and the pop method removes from the end. Both are constant time, because appending and popping at the tail of a dynamic array never require shifting elements.

In Kotlin, the array-deque class serves the same purpose, with add-last for push and remove-last for pop.

The reason the top is always the end of the list, never the front, is performance. Popping from the front would force every remaining element to shift left — linear time. By keeping the top at the end, every stack operation stays constant time.
